    {
      "id": "5b677979_0eb4b246",
      "file_path": "models-tosca/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/models/tosca/simple/concepts/JpaToscaProperty.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 220,
      "message": "Looking at what I did on the policy metadata, it's OK to be null in the database and if it's null in the database, it's passed back as null in the authorative concept.\n\nHowever, it's never actually null because the fromAuthorative() method in the JpaToscaPolicy class has this:\n\n\n        // Add the property metadata if it doesn't exist already\n        if (toscaPolicy.getMetadata() == null) {\n            setMetadata(new LinkedHashMap<>());\n        }\n\n        // Add the policy name and version fields to the metadata\n        getMetadata().put(METADATA_POLICY_ID_TAG, getKey().getName());\n        getMetadata().put(METADATA_POLICY_VERSION_TAG, Integer.toString(getKey().getMajorVersion()));\n\nIt looks like the value of \"matchable\" always comes in from the TOSCA policy, so then I don't think you need to do anything.\n\nIn the JpaToscaPolicy, we had to add metadata because the name and version have to be added \"magically\" by the system.\n\nSo in summary, I think what you have is fine. We should write a few test cases to try it out, or just extend the existing test classes.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2787,
        "name": "Liam Fallon",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
        "username": "liamfallon"
      },
      "updated": "2019-09-09 12:46:27.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "e2b785eb_575c943c",
      "unresolved": true
